<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/Sport/Article&sz=300x250&c=1446560337&t=artid%3d8a203849-dd6d-4605-9df3-e19766ec6301%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/Sport/Article&sz=300x250&c=1446560337&t=artid%3d8a203849-dd6d-4605-9df3-e19766ec6301%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>Chippa have scored 10 goals in 12 league matches so far, six goals fewer than pacesetters Baroka FC. Although Teboho Moloi’s charges are in comfortable seventh spot in the table, Mpengesi reckons they will do better in the final third of the pitch if they get a prolific scorer. His team has the second most draws in the league, along with Kaizer Chiefs, having drawn seven in total. Golden Arrows have drawn eight.Said Mpengesi: “We have decided to look outside the country because we could not find the type of striker we need locally. We have one spot open for a foreigner. “The local strikers have been going through a rough patch and that makes it difficult to sign someone who might need longer to adapt and start scoring goals. We need someone who will hit the ground running to help us finish the season in a better position than we did last season.”Mpengesi revealed that they have given up on their mission to lure out-of-favour Kaizer Chiefs winger William Twala back to their stable. The speedy player has struggled to obtain a regular place in Steve Komphela’s lineup this season. Speculation is rife that Twala will join Free State Stars in the January transfer window in a swap deal that will see Sinethemba Jantjie wear the gold and black jersey. “It would be nice to have Twala back, but we can’t afford to pay his huge salary.”But Chiefs boss Bobby Motaung says the technical staff have yet to decide which players they will release.“We’ll make an announcement when the time is right.”
